Daniel handles the business side.
Feel free to reach out to any of us — our emails are available.

17
00:11:49,390 --> 00:11:53,170
Alright. Let me quickly outline
where we're going today.

18
00:11:53,210 --> 00:11:55,030
Here's roughly the structure:

19
00:11:56,290 --> 00:12:00,030
We'll talk about what traditional photoshoots involve,

20
00:12:00,110 --> 00:12:03,940
how things look today — AI photoshoots
are already happening at major companies.

21
00:12:03,950 --> 00:12:07,790
We'll look at real examples.
We'll explain what brand identity is

22
00:12:07,890 --> 00:12:11,570
and how it translates into AI.
We'll discuss how to apply brand identity in AI,

23
00:12:11,570 --> 00:12:16,102
how to work as a creative director
inside the system,

24
00:12:16,122 --> 00:12:19,022
and how to use references from the real world.

25
00:12:20,110 --> 00:12:23,590
Then we'll get into prompt editing and refinement —

26
00:12:23,590 --> 00:12:30,250
making sure you consistently get strong output
with fewer bugs and artifacts.

27
00:12:30,290 --> 00:12:34,170
After that, how to turn that work into templates
so you can run shoots faster —

28
00:12:34,190 --> 00:12:35,590
that's the core of the "scale up" I mentioned.

29
00:12:35,590 --> 00:12:38,382
How to use the Describe tool to bring
existing client assets into the AI world.

30
00:12:38,442 --> 00:12:39,282
How to deliver a digital product to a client.

31
00:12:39,282 --> 00:12:46,642
What we're building at Astria is a system that enables
a real dialogue between creative professionals and brands.

32
00:12:46,682 --> 00:12:50,042
We don't just deliver images — and then all the work is wasted.
We deliver a digital product: a template.

33
00:12:51,802 --> 00:12:54,992
Finally, the brand or the creative runs the looks themselves.
And then a few closing thoughts.

34
00:12:55,082 --> 00:12:58,662
That's the structure. So let me start with
a quick overview — what do I mean when I say

35
00:12:59,162 --> 00:13:03,082
"AI photoshoot"? I mean everything that involves
the logistics of a traditional shoot:

36
00:13:03,122 --> 00:13:04,002
coordinating models,

37
00:13:04,862 --> 00:13:07,682
locations, shipping all the inventory —
making sure product arrives

38
00:13:07,682 --> 00:13:09,882
from production to the shoot day.

39
00:13:09,962 --> 00:13:13,762
Stylists, makeup, hair —
all of that logistics

40
00:13:14,142 --> 00:13:17,702
ultimately exists to serve the brand's DNA.

41
00:13:22,922 --> 00:13:26,642
The whole photoshoot is there to convey
the brand identity,

42
00:13:26,682 --> 00:13:30,042
and we need to somehow implement and communicate that.

43
00:13:30,042 --> 00:13:35,942
I want to step back for a moment to what Hila said.
I also come from a technical background — machine learning, coding —

44
00:13:35,942 --> 00:13:39,422
and my world has changed a lot too.
Everyone codes in Claude now.

45
00:13:39,422 --> 00:13:43,310
I've largely stopped writing code myself.
I've moved more toward product thinking —

46
00:13:43,310 --> 00:13:50,042
directing at a higher level. That doesn't mean
I don't need to understand what's happening underneath.

47
00:13:50,042 --> 00:13:54,342
The same applies here. Creative professionals,
photographers — they're absolutely not being replaced.

48
00:13:54,342 --> 00:13:57,842
But you still need to guide the system.
You need to know how to work with a brand,

49
00:13:57,842 --> 00:14:02,972
understand its DNA, apply it, and direct the AI.
Without that, there's no context —

50
00:14:03,442 --> 00:14:07,022
and you can't produce anything distinctive.

51
00:14:07,042 --> 00:14:09,882
Part of not looking like AI
is creating differentiation —

52
00:14:09,962 --> 00:14:13,762
a very distinctive aesthetic.
We'll talk about that.

53
00:14:14,142 --> 00:14:17,702
So — what kinds of brands are we talking about?

54
00:14:17,722 --> 00:14:21,222
Brands in the e-commerce space,
DTC — direct to consumer —

55
00:14:21,242 --> 00:14:21,762
brands selling directly to consumers
without physical retail,

56
00:14:22,922 --> 00:14:26,642
as well as retailers with stores.
The verticals relevant to today's session

57
00:14:26,662 --> 00:14:27,782
are fashion and apparel —

58
00:14:29,162 --> 00:14:32,982
shirts, jackets, pants, dresses, wedding dresses,

59
00:14:33,582 --> 00:14:33,842
footwear,

60
00:14:35,162 --> 00:14:38,982
outdoor and trekking gear, bags, handbags,

61
00:14:39,082 --> 00:14:42,842
jewelry — and when I say jewelry
I mean independent jewelers more than diamond companies.

62
00:14:46,702 --> 00:14:47,622
Also eyewear.

63
00:14:48,602 --> 00:14:52,562
Eyewear companies have a strong DNA
in how they look and present themselves.

64
00:14:52,622 --> 00:14:56,462
This next slide shows that the AI world
is already here and operational.

65
00:14:56,502 --> 00:17:00,482
This is an example of a campaign for Saks —
actually not a campaign, they transformed

66
00:17:00,522 --> 00:17:04,362
their site with the help of Shai Yechezkel,
a photographer who works with us as a real partner.

67
00:17:04,372 --> 00:17:08,142
You're seeing the entire website —
it's all generated

68
00:17:08,162 --> 00:17:11,662
with Shai's work. He brought the creative eye,
built their model set,

69
00:17:12,482 --> 00:17:14,782
built the template set,

70
00:17:15,782 --> 00:17:19,182
and then ran all the looks
to produce the full collection.

71
00:17:19,302 --> 00:17:20,182
They're now

72
00:17:21,342 --> 00:17:25,002
on their second collection — and everything is generated.

73
00:17:25,022 --> 00:17:28,962
Another example: Nine West,
already using AI for

74
00:17:28,962 --> 00:17:32,462
in-store signage, back-of-checkout displays,
and billboards.

75
00:17:33,522 --> 00:17:36,862
Then there's Ronit Alkabetz — a Paris-based
elite designer working with AI.

76
00:17:37,402 --> 00:17:41,130
All of this was done in Astria.
And of course there are also

77
00:17:41,130 --> 00:17:44,562
the big players — Mango, H&M, Zara —
they're all working in AI,

78
00:17:44,562 --> 00:17:48,742
producing both campaigns and lookbooks.
The world is already there de facto.

79
00:17:48,782 --> 00:17:52,032
What remains is to direct it well,
scale it up, and do it precisely.

80
00:17:52,032 --> 00:18:01,206
So let's talk about brand identity
and how to create something truly special.

81
00:18:01,206 --> 00:18:05,206
We're looking at a demo we built for a fictitious Zara.
This was created by Sivan Aharon,

82
00:18:05,206 --> 00:18:09,082
who's part of this community,
and you can see how there's a set of templates

83
00:18:09,082 --> 00:18:11,662
for different types of garments —
pants, shoes, shirts,

84
00:18:11,662 --> 00:18:12,946
dresses, jackets,

85
00:18:13,326 --> 00:18:16,746
heels. Each one speaks a different language
and requires different templates

86
00:18:16,962 --> 00:18:20,302
and different refinements.
You can see that everything here is clickable —

87
00:18:20,302 --> 00:18:24,782
there's a set of studio images,
and Zara in particular has moved

88
00:18:24,822 --> 00:18:28,482
all of their lookbooks toward outdoor photography,
which is why we see those options here.

89
00:18:29,102 --> 00:18:33,042
What we're really showing is how we implement
a brand's visual language in AI —

90
00:18:33,042 --> 00:18:36,346
how this speaks in the language of Zara.

91
00:18:36,346 --> 00:18:38,346
Let me show a few more examples.

92
00:18:38,346 --> 00:18:42,046
A sportswear brand modeled more around Adidas.
You can see the slightly more intense expressions,

93
00:18:42,046 --> 00:18:45,302
the athletic energy. Here too

94
00:18:45,302 --> 00:18:47,906
there's a set of templates
that brands can pick up and use.

95
00:19:12,106 --> 00:19:15,706
We've already had companies that took these templates
off the shelf and said:

96
00:19:15,766 --> 00:19:19,586
"This is beautiful, but it's not my brand. It's not me."

97
00:19:22,726 --> 00:19:26,106
And that's exactly the important thing to recognize
when working with brands.

98
00:19:26,226 --> 00:19:29,746
You need to ask: who is the target audience?
What's their age range?

99
00:19:33,766 --> 00:19:34,286
What are the client's existing materials?
What brief do they give you?

100
00:19:41,586 --> 00:19:42,066
How should the models look?

101
00:19:43,486 --> 00:19:47,406
Short hair? Gel?

102
00:19:47,626 --> 00:19:49,446
I don't come from this world,
so forgive me

103
00:19:50,786 --> 00:19:54,766
for not knowing all the precise terminology —
but that's exactly the point.

104
00:19:54,786 --> 00:19:58,636
This is why it matters.
Here's another example —

105
00:20:08,726 --> 00:20:11,946
a basics brand modeled more
around Uniqlo, similar to brands like

106
00:20:11,966 --> 00:20:17,586
Fox — hoodies, that kind of thing.
You can see there are several distinct brand types here,

107
00:20:17,586 --> 00:20:24,026
all illustrating this idea of brand identity.
Each brand has its own background color,

108
00:20:24,026 --> 00:20:27,666
its own hex values, its own expressions,
its own set of models

109
00:20:27,666 --> 00:20:31,446
that define it — so when you see it you say,
"That's that brand.

110
00:20:31,486 --> 00:20:35,306
That look, that feel, it's right for that age group,
that type of person,

111
00:20:35,346 --> 00:20:39,296
that atmosphere."

112
00:20:39,326 --> 00:20:42,976
So how do we actually build this in Astria,
and how did we decide

113
00:20:43,366 --> 00:20:47,046
to translate it into a product?

114
00:20:57,126 --> 00:21:02,322
Tali, I think you're not on mute.

115
00:21:16,306 --> 00:21:20,086
So at Astria there's a core concept
of templatization — templates.

116
00:21:20,566 --> 00:21:24,005
We take prompts, group them together,
and turn them into a single template.

117
00:21:24,186 --> 00:21:27,666
Those who know Astria from before —
this used to be called a pack.

118
00:21:27,766 --> 00:21:31,266
We're moving away from that term.
Today we call it a template.

119
00:21:31,386 --> 00:21:34,506
You can see here the example of the template
I started showing earlier.

120
00:21:38,442 --> 00:21:41,186
This is the idea behind
what we want to deliver to the brand.

121
00:21:41,706 --> 00:21:45,802
We want to create a workspace for them.
Workspaces are up here at the top.

122
00:21:46,806 --> 00:21:50,066
We open one workspace per brand
to keep clients separate.

123
00:21:50,206 --> 00:21:51,546
Clients also sit within the workspace —

124
00:21:52,786 --> 00:21:54,986
they're added to the workspace,
they put in their credit card,

125
00:21:57,126 --> 00:21:59,196
and generations are charged to the client.
They can see all materials.

126
00:22:00,346 --> 00:22:04,146
This is part of what matters to clients —
it gives them confidence,

127
00:22:04,266 --> 00:22:08,126
because once the collection or campaign is done,
their assets keep living and breathing.

128
00:22:08,186 --> 00:22:12,026
They receive templates they can continue
to develop and refine over time,

129
00:22:12,066 --> 00:22:16,046
growing them and keeping up with trends.

130
00:22:16,086 --> 00:22:17,306
So here you can see how you can simply take

131
00:22:17,966 --> 00:22:21,167
a different dress and run the same templates

132
00:22:21,167 --> 00:22:23,446
to get similar images.

133
00:22:23,706 --> 00:22:27,946
In a lookbook that's completely fine —
most brands want a consistent-looking lookbook.

134
00:22:27,946 --> 00:22:31,006
Some want very precise uniformity,
others want some variation.

135
00:22:31,066 --> 00:22:35,306
And that's one of those layers
you can control through the right prompt —

136
00:22:35,346 --> 00:22:38,766
either high precision or, conversely,
allowing some randomness.

137
00:22:38,806 --> 00:22:42,206
There's also a feature called Brief
which allows you to generate variety.

138
00:22:42,482 --> 00:22:45,802
Here's the key point — and I've said it once
but I want to say it from a different angle:

139
00:22:45,842 --> 00:22:49,422
brands generally need help.
They cannot make this transition alone.

140
00:22:49,982 --> 00:22:53,822
They don't understand AI, they don't know
how to write prompts, they don't know

141
00:22:53,842 --> 00:22:56,881
what nano banana is. A lot of the time
they want to hand things off

142
00:22:57,262 --> 00:25:01,142
and have someone help them — send over the looks,
the items, and get assistance.

143
00:25:01,162 --> 00:25:04,542
That's exactly why the templatization concept exists.
Someone needs to come in and help them

144
00:25:04,862 --> 00:25:09,142
make that transition. The platform
enables the abstraction and the collaboration.

145
00:25:09,182 --> 00:25:12,822
Six months ago it was LoRA with Flux.
Then it was nano banana Gemini 2.5.

146
00:25:12,862 --> 00:25:15,622
Today it's nano banana 2.
The brand doesn't care and doesn't want to know.

147
00:25:26,862 --> 00:25:28,142
And it doesn't end with building the templates.

148
00:25:28,682 --> 00:25:32,302
If today it's nano banana 2,
in two months they'll need help

149
00:25:32,342 --> 00:25:35,442
upgrading to nano banana 3, to seed dream

150
00:25:35,442 --> 00:25:42,262
and seed dance 2. If today they need still images,
tomorrow they'll need video,

151
00:25:42,262 --> 00:25:46,262
the day after — multi-format.
The technology keeps evolving.

152
00:25:46,262 --> 00:25:50,302
Think about how it was predicted that the vacuum cleaner
would replace the cleaner's job.

153
00:25:50,302 --> 00:25:54,342
It didn't — the standard just went up.
Or that computers and 3D would replace animators.

154
00:25:54,342 --> 00:25:58,422
They didn't — there are just far more films
being made, and the bar rose.

155
00:25:58,422 --> 00:26:02,522
The same is true here. There's a need to produce
far more media,

156
00:26:02,522 --> 00:26:06,882
more variety, more differentiation,
and I think this technology

157
00:26:06,882 --> 00:26:09,952
is in many ways, as they say in English,
leveling the playing field.

158
00:26:09,952 --> 00:26:14,042
It allows players who couldn't previously produce
high-quality content

159
00:26:14,042 --> 00:26:18,566
to now do so.

160
00:26:18,566 --> 00:26:22,362
So — coming back to the practical side.
We're looking at a template the brand receives.

161
00:26:22,502 --> 00:26:26,122
Someone in the studio can simply click Upload,
upload a photo from a hanger and run it,

162
00:26:26,162 --> 00:26:29,502
and receive a lookbook with a single click —
without having to define anything.

163
00:26:29,502 --> 00:26:33,162
The framework was already defined for them —
the models, everything.

164
00:26:33,162 --> 00:26:37,742
They can of course override things.
Some of Astria's features allow for variation —

165
00:26:37,782 --> 00:26:41,362
say we want to shift the mood slightly,
or add some accessory and say,

166
00:26:41,402 --> 00:26:44,282
"This time she's sitting on an armchair," —
that's the Brief concept.

167
00:26:44,382 --> 00:26:48,122
It still runs the entire template
under one coherent idea.

168
00:26:48,162 --> 00:26:51,982
You can change the bag, you can change the model,
but at the core — the product this template is selling

169
00:26:51,982 --> 00:26:55,242
is the dress. And first and foremost,
you can customize the dress.

170
00:26:55,242 --> 00:26:58,942
Beyond that, you can of course run thirty dresses
with a single click

171
00:26:58,982 --> 00:27:03,082
and get all the output at once.

172
00:27:03,082 --> 00:27:06,082
That's the key thing. And how does the brand
see the full collection?

173
00:27:06,082 --> 00:27:09,342
They don't just need one template —
they need a set of templates,

174
00:27:09,342 --> 00:27:13,082
because each garment type behaves differently.
A jacket requires different crops

175
00:27:13,082 --> 00:27:16,962
and different details than shoes,
and different model positioning,

176
00:27:16,962 --> 00:27:20,566
and probably outdoor photography too.
So the brand needs a set of templates,

177
00:27:20,566 --> 00:27:24,086
and they see this through their template page.
They can choose: now I want to run dresses,

178
00:27:24,086 --> 00:27:27,946
now shirts, now boots. That's what the brand sees.

179
00:27:27,946 --> 00:27:31,058
Now let's look at how we actually create
and deliver this.

180
00:27:31,258 --> 00:27:34,542
Now we're getting to the more practical part —
everyone is welcome to open the link from earlier

181
00:27:34,622 --> 00:27:38,602
