[In response to a question about Pack Shot:]
Yes — which means you can also shoot it with your iPhone.

221
00:36:47,326 --> 00:36:47,686
Right.

222
00:36:48,546 --> 00:36:52,146
If you're a small designer with no Pack Shot —
just a decent iPhone photo —

223
00:36:52,586 --> 00:36:56,436
that's fine. But what you need to understand
is this has nothing to do with

224
00:36:56,446 --> 00:36:58,126
the Astria system itself.

225
00:36:59,186 --> 00:37:03,146
The system runs on technologies like nano banana, Flux,
and others.

226
00:37:03,226 --> 00:37:06,676
What happens is we're showing something to the AI —
I show it this sweater,

227
00:37:06,786 --> 00:37:10,616
I tell it to put it on a model.
I can photograph it on a hanger, on the floor, on a mannequin,

228
00:37:10,616 --> 00:37:14,882
and it will dress a model with it.
But yes — photo quality matters

229
00:37:14,882 --> 00:37:18,166
in terms of how much texture and detail
the AI can see.

230
00:37:18,246 --> 00:37:22,106
If I shoot under my room lighting
with shadows falling across the sweater

231
00:37:22,146 --> 00:37:26,106
and it looks distorted — the AI will struggle
to understand how that sweater should look.

232
00:37:26,126 --> 00:37:29,986
If I photograph it properly — I'd even invest
in some lighting because it's worth it.

233
00:37:29,986 --> 00:37:33,366
It saves me shooting days. I point the light at the sweater,
style it correctly,

234
00:37:33,366 --> 00:37:37,166
and then use it — and the image will be sharper,
textures will be much more visible.

235
00:37:37,166 --> 00:37:41,056
Whether it's a Pack Shot or a regular photo
does change the game.

236
00:37:41,086 --> 00:37:44,766
But even without a professional Pack Shot
it's still possible to create great things.

237
00:37:59,762 --> 00:38:00,946
No — not needed.

238
00:38:02,286 --> 00:38:06,086
[In response to a question about training models per garment:]
If it's a Pack Shot or a regular photo —
that does change the rules of the game.

239
00:38:06,546 --> 00:38:10,366
But even those who can't do professional Pack Shots
can still create output with this.

240
00:38:37,526 --> 00:38:41,056
No, no, no. What he'll teach you
is how to show the item from every angle —

241
00:38:56,026 --> 00:38:56,766
Workspace.

242
00:38:57,022 --> 00:38:57,682
Workspace.

243
00:39:29,606 --> 00:39:33,186
Yes — so it's possible that you didn't select a background,
so just click Pick a Color

244
00:39:33,226 --> 00:39:36,106
and that will give you a uniform color.

245
00:39:36,186 --> 00:39:39,426
Since the technology isn't perfect yet,
it needs you —

246
00:39:39,426 --> 00:39:42,546
because things happen.

247
00:39:42,686 --> 00:40:02,046
Not in this system, but in Midjourney for example —
I want a girl standing in a forest,

248
00:40:02,046 --> 00:40:04,206
and no matter what I do,
it keeps giving me a medium shot.

249
00:40:04,206 --> 00:40:09,226
It doesn't show her feet, no matter what I write —
Wide Shot, describing her shoes.

250
00:40:09,226 --> 00:40:13,346
But if I describe "the girl touching the ground"
— suddenly it gives me the full body shot.

251
00:42:16,206 --> 00:42:17,606
Can everyone see the screen?

252
00:42:18,786 --> 00:42:20,846
So — where we left off:
how to actually create these templates.

253
00:42:21,126 --> 00:42:23,386
I hope everyone is safe and OK.

254
00:42:25,786 --> 00:42:29,506
There's a new button here called Lookbook
which helps us

255
00:42:29,606 --> 00:42:33,166
get started with prompts and begin creating
what we want.

256
00:42:33,246 --> 00:42:37,226
The first step is simply to drag and drop,

257
00:42:37,326 --> 00:42:41,006
or upload, your references.
Let's say we start working with a shirt and pants —

258
00:42:41,646 --> 00:42:45,286
and they happen to be available.
We have a public gallery

259
00:42:45,606 --> 00:42:49,526
of models and

260
00:42:49,586 --> 00:42:53,046
shirts and pants just to make it easy
to demonstrate.

261
00:43:06,162 --> 00:43:09,322
She's asking about the Try tab — what clients see.

262
00:43:11,182 --> 00:43:11,682
The...?

263
00:43:12,462 --> 00:43:13,242
The tab.

264
00:43:13,782 --> 00:43:15,032
She means the Workspace.

265
00:43:15,082 --> 00:43:15,802
Workspace.

266
00:43:16,282 --> 00:43:19,922
In the dropdown at the top
there's an option to work in Workspaces.

267
00:43:19,962 --> 00:43:23,642
If you click there, you can Add a new workspace
and create a workspace scoped

268
00:43:23,682 --> 00:43:27,502
to the organization you're working with.

269
00:43:38,562 --> 00:43:39,002
OK.

270
00:43:39,982 --> 00:43:43,902
No problem — we'll fix that.
But for now,

271
00:43:43,922 --> 00:43:44,422
just —

272
00:43:44,642 --> 00:43:48,472
just go through the Generate window,
which is the same window —

273
00:43:48,502 --> 00:43:49,722
and the button will be added for you.

274
00:43:52,722 --> 00:43:53,552
Click on Generate.

275
00:43:53,582 --> 00:43:57,242
Use the link in the chat — you'll be able
to open a new workspace and then

276
00:43:57,631 --> 00:44:00,802
you'll see that dropdown.

277
00:44:00,832 --> 00:44:03,802
It's just not open to everyone by default.

278
00:44:06,852 --> 00:44:08,882
Can everyone see the Generate window?

279
00:44:08,962 --> 00:44:12,842
Click Generate —
and if you want to see the grid squares,

280
00:44:15,162 --> 00:44:16,502
Yes — click Lookbook.

281
00:44:33,362 --> 00:44:34,182
So —

282
00:44:36,422 --> 00:44:40,282
the Lookbook is essentially a prompt builder
designed to be a bit more visual.

283
00:44:40,302 --> 00:44:43,862
It doesn't replace anything —
it doesn't do anything behind the scenes.

284
00:44:43,902 --> 00:44:47,322
You can actually see the prompt
being built in the background.

285
00:44:47,382 --> 00:44:48,362
Let's take some examples.

286
00:44:49,202 --> 00:44:52,262
The simplest example: take a model's face,
a shirt, jeans.

287
00:44:52,422 --> 00:44:55,082
And I'll even drag in some shoes

288
00:44:55,942 --> 00:44:59,842
— for the demo I'll also add

289
00:45:06,341 --> 00:45:08,642
some shoes I'll search for.

290
00:45:11,372 --> 00:45:13,242
[setting up demo]

291
00:45:14,302 --> 00:45:15,502
She's not registered by the way.

292
00:45:15,622 --> 00:45:18,442
In principle you can also just copy-paste things in.

293
00:45:28,832 --> 00:45:30,762
I don't know who that background noise was —
please put yourself on mute.

294
00:45:37,022 --> 00:45:40,982
[In response to a question about using a pre-built character:]
This isn't a character sheet.
Here it's just the face.

295
00:45:40,982 --> 00:45:44,766
It's best to use just the face,
from the neck up — no clothes.

296
00:45:44,882 --> 00:45:45,222
Yes —

297
00:45:45,422 --> 00:45:57,562
It's just a photo of the model —
no special setup needed.
This is not like what we did before.

298
00:45:57,622 --> 00:45:59,502
Let me give a few tips on references.

299
00:46:00,762 --> 00:46:04,262
First — technically, to upload things
there are a few ways:

300
00:46:04,262 --> 00:46:07,522
click the plus sign here, and a picker opens —
similar to Google Flow —

301
00:46:07,522 --> 00:46:10,542
with an Upload button.
You can also drag directly.

302
00:46:10,542 --> 00:46:15,462
It recognizes the type of item
and adds the thumbnail.

303
00:46:15,522 --> 00:46:18,542
I'll do a copy-paste here.
You can't see my desktop,

304
00:46:18,542 --> 00:46:22,462
but I'll paste the shoes in —
and you'll see it uploads them and adds them.

305
00:46:22,462 --> 00:46:26,442
So now we have:
model, shirt, pants, shoes — that's the basic.

306
00:46:26,442 --> 00:46:29,282
Let's also add a background.
There's a Color Picker here too.

307
00:46:29,282 --> 00:46:34,382
You can't see it right now,
but for those who try — it's very important for brands

308
00:46:34,382 --> 00:46:38,382
that when you open their page,
things are consistent with the same background.

309
00:46:38,382 --> 00:46:42,862
A uniform background is very, very important.
We even have a post-processing step

310
00:46:42,862 --> 00:46:46,922
that works a bit like Photoshop to ensure consistency,
because nano banana doesn't always listen.

311
00:46:46,922 --> 00:46:50,022
If you tell it white background FFF,
it doesn't always do that.

312
00:46:50,022 --> 00:46:54,922
So we have a post-processing step afterward
to help enforce that.

313
00:46:54,962 --> 00:46:57,522
Now — a bit about the technical parameters.
Today the recommended model to work with is nano banana 2.

314
00:46:57,522 --> 00:47:01,042
It's the most accurate and the fastest.

315
00:47:01,042 --> 00:47:06,622
3×4 is how most product pages are built today.
2K is my recommendation —

316
00:47:06,622 --> 00:47:10,742
it's a good balance between cost and quality.
If you're happy with something,

317
00:47:10,742 --> 00:47:13,002
you can consider going up to 4K.
Just note that 4K is very,

318
00:47:13,002 --> 00:47:16,342
very slow — and Google is struggling
to supply enough compute these days.

319
00:47:16,342 --> 00:47:20,322
Sometimes you'll see errors
when we're handling the most requests.

320
00:47:20,322 --> 00:47:24,982
We're constantly working to keep the system
as stable as possible. We have fallbacks,

321
00:47:24,982 --> 00:47:28,382
we pay Google extra just to get enough quota —
and still, sometimes there are overloads.

322
00:47:28,422 --> 00:47:31,342
So my recommendation is —

323
00:47:41,042 --> 00:47:44,962
[In response to a question about model source images:]
Yes — if you upload a character created in Midjourney,
just drag-and-drop into the prompt box and it will work.

324
00:47:44,962 --> 00:47:49,022
No, no, no. Everything is private.
Everything lives under your Workspace

325
00:47:49,022 --> 00:47:53,362
and is private to the people in that Workspace.

326
00:47:53,422 --> 00:47:57,242
Nothing — we've eliminated public galleries.
We understand the privacy concern.

327
00:47:57,262 --> 00:48:01,102
We're removing everything public.
There's no more public feed.

328
00:48:01,102 --> 00:48:04,742
Except for packs or templates
you actively choose to publish.

329
00:48:04,742 --> 00:48:08,382
By default, everything is private.

330
00:48:08,422 --> 00:48:11,342
[In response to a question about the color picker:]
There's a button here called Pick a Color.

331
00:48:11,342 --> 00:48:14,126
It opens a system dialog —
by default it opens in RGB,

332
00:48:14,146 --> 00:48:17,666
but you can click it
and choose a hex value.

333
00:48:20,166 --> 00:48:22,446
And the best approach here —

334
00:48:23,686 --> 00:48:27,666
really go to the brand's website
and sample the hex color directly,

335
00:48:27,686 --> 00:48:30,246
color by color.

336
00:48:31,086 --> 00:48:34,926
You can see the prompt being built
step by step — and there's almost no text here.

337
00:48:34,926 --> 00:48:38,766
I'll generate — and you can see
a prompt is formed, processed —

338
00:48:38,766 --> 00:48:49,602
almost no text at all. Let me explain something:
there's a common assumption that if you write

339
00:48:49,602 --> 00:48:53,246
a complex prompt with extra-realistic faces
that will make all the difference.

340
00:48:53,246 --> 00:48:58,662
That's nice and important —
but I don't think that's where the real value lies.

341
00:48:58,662 --> 00:49:02,306
The value is in the precision of the details —
knowing where to work with the model

342
00:49:02,306 --> 00:49:06,002
even when it's hard to get it
to avoid mistakes.

343
00:49:06,002 --> 00:49:10,046
Knowing to pay attention to the brand's specifics matters.
You only see that after iterations —

344
00:49:10,046 --> 00:49:13,766
after generating and running maybe ten looks,
suddenly realizing:

345
00:49:13,766 --> 00:49:16,886
the shirt needs to be untucked.
It's not a complex prompt.

346
00:49:16,926 --> 00:49:20,286
Just write "untucked shirt."

347
00:49:20,286 --> 00:49:25,946
Or the brand wants different facial expressions —
"change random mimics."

348
00:49:25,946 --> 00:49:30,206
Or write "smiling." Same thing —
if you want to work in the Lookbook,

349
00:49:30,206 --> 00:49:34,011
you can type it right here and it's a bit more visual.
I can type "smiling, untucked shirt."

350
00:49:34,042 --> 00:49:38,062
Now a few more tips on references.
I uploaded a shoe from the side view.

351
00:49:38,062 --> 00:49:41,326
Not recommended — not a great idea.
That's just what I had from the website.

352
00:49:41,326 --> 00:49:44,742
I recommend uploading shoes at 45 degrees —
two shoes, without a person.

353
00:49:44,742 --> 00:49:48,522
For garment references — you can ask the brand
for what's called a flat lay:

354
00:49:48,522 --> 00:49:51,146
on a table, good lighting. You can also use a hanger —

355
00:49:51,146 --> 00:49:55,306
it's generally less ideal but workable.

356
00:49:55,946 --> 00:49:59,886
Depending on the brand and different sensitivities,
this works very, very well.

357
00:52:13,226 --> 00:52:16,966
[In response to a question about Pack Shot vs. on-body:]
It's a question that gets a bit more technical,
but let me explain.

358
00:52:16,966 --> 00:52:22,586
AI models love statistics. They work based on
what's prevalent in popular culture.

359
00:52:22,586 --> 00:52:26,266
If the jeans are standard —
if it's a garment the model has seen before

360
00:52:26,266 --> 00:52:31,126
and was trained on — it'll probably know
how to reproduce it.

361
00:52:31,126 --> 00:52:34,786
Let me give an extreme example from something we saw:
a brand we worked with had a logo that changed.

362
00:52:34,786 --> 00:52:38,646
It had a crest with text on it —
but in an older version the text was at the top.

363
00:52:38,646 --> 00:52:42,886
It's a very well-known brand,
and the models were trained on the entire internet —

364
00:52:42,886 --> 00:52:47,366
they learned the text was on top.
No matter how many times you tried to give it the reference,

365
00:52:47,366 --> 00:52:51,126
it kept generating the old version.

366
00:52:51,126 --> 00:52:54,786
So that's an example of how models work
based on what they learned from the past.

367
00:52:54,786 --> 00:52:58,646
The same applies here. It depends on whether
the garment is unique — or something the model knows well.

368
00:52:58,646 --> 00:53:02,866
And for unique items, there's trial and error.
A lot of the time there's

369
00:53:02,866 --> 00:53:07,086
another layer — whether it's something
you and I can describe and articulate.

370
00:53:07,086 --> 00:53:11,606
The cut, the fit, the length of the dress.
If we can say — below the knee, above the knee,

371
00:53:11,606 --> 00:53:15,546
three-quarter length — then the model can say it too.
If we don't know, neither does it.

372
00:53:15,546 --> 00:53:21,485
Then it might make sense to put it on a mannequin or dress form.
That's more work —

373
00:53:21,626 --> 00:53:25,566
but that's one option. Another option
is to specify it at the generation level —

374
00:53:25,566 --> 00:53:29,006
add detail to that specific garment's generation.
Write "balloon pants" and it comes out perfect.

375
00:53:29,006 --> 00:53:33,006
But that requires an eye that knows —
"I can see this won't come out right,

376
00:53:33,006 --> 00:53:36,826
I know what it needs, I'll fix it." And sometimes
things just need that attention.

377
00:53:36,946 --> 00:53:40,846
More things that help with references
for getting good results.

378
00:53:40,906 --> 00:53:43,826
Your references should be clean.
But there are editing tools —

379
00:53:43,826 --> 00:53:47,786
if you're shooting on a hanger or similar,
there's a wrench icon here

380
00:53:47,786 --> 00:53:51,062
where you can do Remove Background —
remove any messiness from the background.

381
00:53:51,062 --> 00:53:55,082
Crop — to crop the garment precisely
and remove things like other hangers

382
00:53:55,082 --> 00:53:58,646
that were in the background.
There's also an Edit with nano banana tool —

383
00:53:58,646 --> 00:54:02,562
where you can literally say:
"Turn into an iron flat lay" —

384
00:54:02,562 --> 00:54:04,562
and it converts something on a hanger
into a flat lay

385
00:54:04,562 --> 00:54:07,642
that looks cleaner and more polished.

386
00:54:07,682 --> 00:54:11,082
This can sometimes affect accuracy.
Usually it works well.

387
00:54:11,082 --> 00:54:15,282
You need to know how to use these tools
and decide your approach based on

388
00:54:15,282 --> 00:54:18,022
how you decided to photograph the references.

389
00:54:18,022 --> 00:54:21,962
That's broadly it. You could go much deeper,
but that's the general idea.

390
00:55:15,582 --> 00:55:16,232
That is —

391
00:55:16,242 --> 00:55:20,082
[In response to a question about background types:]
We'll get to that shortly.
We started from the Lookbook helper —

392
00:55:20,182 --> 00:55:24,172
the most visual way in — for more special use cases. But —

393
00:55:32,742 --> 00:55:34,422
Here I'm only dealing with a solid color, right?

394
00:55:44,722 --> 00:55:48,402
Of course. Just like you uploaded a shirt,
you can click the picker,

395
00:55:48,422 --> 00:55:52,102
hit Upload, and upload a background image.
Or even better — just describe it.

396
00:55:52,142 --> 00:55:55,582
You can write "on a Parisian

397
00:55:55,682 --> 00:55:59,722
bridge." Let's try it just for fun.

398
00:55:59,722 --> 00:57:06,882
Yes, you really don't need more than that.
No elaborate prompt needed.

399
00:57:06,882 --> 00:57:10,782
I'm a fan of prompts up to about three lines,
maximum around 200 words —

400
00:57:10,782 --> 00:57:13,122
that's great. But the important part

401
00:57:13,122 --> 00:57:16,822
of working with references is the balance
between references and text.

402
00:57:16,822 --> 00:57:20,682
Sometimes it's worth using image references —
for style references for example.

403
00:57:20,682 --> 00:57:24,522
Say the brand sells shoes
but we also need to style pants.

404
00:57:24,522 --> 00:57:28,922
We can decide whether the templates we create
will use image references for pants —

405
00:57:28,922 --> 00:57:33,341
actual photos to upload — in which case
when the brand wants variety they actually need to bring

406
00:57:33,382 --> 00:57:37,222
a different pants reference.
Or we can just write it as text — like "blue chinos" —

407
00:57:37,222 --> 00:57:39,222
something like that.

408
00:57:39,222 --> 00:57:42,522
And then the template is textually flexible
and editable via the brief.

409
00:57:42,522 --> 00:57:45,022
There's a certain playfulness here
you need to learn.

410
00:57:45,022 --> 00:57:49,362
Also note — don't include shoes
if you want a medium shot.

411
00:57:49,482 --> 00:57:53,462
Or if you want jewelry,
don't include the whole outfit —

412
00:57:53,482 --> 00:57:56,281
it can confuse the model.
If you want medium and you give it shoes,

413
00:57:56,281 --> 00:57:58,402
it'll show the whole body.
Watch out for that.

414
00:57:58,402 --> 00:58:02,062
Yes — there's a lot of room for bugs here.
If we want a close-up of the shoes,

415
00:58:02,062 --> 00:58:06,162
but we give it a face,
it'll try to fit the face in somewhere

416
00:58:06,162 --> 00:58:10,442
and create distorted figures —
because it's trying to include both

417
00:58:10,442 --> 00:58:13,982
the face and the shoes
while you've asked for a medium close-up.

418
00:58:13,982 --> 00:58:16,462
Same thing in reverse — if you want
a shirt close-up but give it shoes,

419
00:58:16,462 --> 00:58:17,582
it won't know what to do.

420
00:58:17,582 --> 00:58:22,002
You need to structure your prompts
so these details are consistent — and free of those bugs.

421
00:58:22,102 --> 00:58:26,002
Let's move forward a bit.
So we started with the Lookbook builder —

422
00:58:26,002 --> 00:58:30,242
more visual and simple.
Now for more complex things,

423
00:58:30,242 --> 00:58:34,882
when you want to describe more —
you can go to the prompt box and define things directly.

424
00:58:43,582 --> 00:58:47,362
Let's take an example here.

425
00:59:57,422 --> 00:59:58,582
Here we go.

426
01:00:07,042 --> 01:00:10,962
You can really go to town on the prompts
and add the key words — small in number

427
01:00:11,022 --> 01:00:14,982
but high in impact.
"Diffused lighting," "realistic skin,"

428
01:00:14,982 --> 01:00:18,662
"soft expression" — things like that.

429
01:00:18,662 --> 01:00:23,162
These are what give it the touch
and the things that matter to the brand —

430
01:00:23,162 --> 01:00:27,082
saying: "The expression of my models is serious,
or they're happy, or pleased."

431
01:00:27,082 --> 01:00:30,562
"This is a children's brand,
this is a low-cost brand,

432
01:00:30,562 --> 01:00:37,882
or this is high-end." What exactly does the brand say?
What does it need to convey?

433
01:00:37,882 --> 01:00:44,762
Let me pause for a moment — I want to show
a feature that helps a lot here.

434
01:00:44,762 --> 01:00:47,986
It's called the Describe tool — this button here.

435
01:00:53,462 --> 01:00:55,122
The Describe tool — this button.

436
01:01:00,122 --> 01:01:03,962
Let me explain what's happening here.
I recorded this demo

437
01:01:03,962 --> 01:01:07,166
when I didn't have a specific brand available —

438
01:01:07,166 --> 01:01:13,026
so I used Pinterest.
In principle, the materials we should use

439
01:01:13,206 --> 01:01:17,166
are the client's existing materials — ones they own the rights to.
But in my case I took Pinterest.

440
01:01:17,496 --> 01:01:21,466
What you can do here is take an image,
copy it,

441
01:01:21,646 --> 01:01:25,506
and paste it into the Describe box.
As you can see, the interface

442
01:01:25,526 --> 01:01:29,366
has changed a bit, but there's a "paste from clipboard" option.

443
01:01:29,366 --> 01:01:33,166
What it does is extract the prompt —
similar to what you may have done in Gemini

444
01:01:33,166 --> 01:01:38,445
or similar tools —
and it describes the prompt, and generates the image.

445
01:01:38,445 --> 01:01:41,106
Let's take an example here.

446
01:01:41,106 --> 01:01:44,686
To simplify: you go to Pinterest,
copy an image, come back,

447
01:01:44,686 --> 01:01:48,266
click Describe and paste —
and it basically converts the image into words.

448
01:01:48,266 --> 01:01:52,326
And the key difference from what you'd do in Gemini
is that it listens to the references you already have

449
01:01:52,326 --> 01:01:56,186
and makes sure not to describe those references.
What can happen otherwise

450
01:01:56,186 --> 01:02:00,046
is a conflict between the prompt
and your references.

451
01:02:00,046 --> 01:02:03,246
For example, it writes "wearing a white shirt"
but your reference is a yellow dress —

452
01:02:03,246 --> 01:02:04,886
and then the model doesn't know what to generate.
It sometimes produces

453
01:02:04,886 --> 01:02:09,606
a yellow dress, sometimes a white shirt —
because there's both a shirt reference and a dress reference.

454
01:02:09,606 --> 01:02:13,466
So you need to be very careful
about conflicts between text and references.

455
01:02:13,466 --> 01:02:15,866
That's part of what the Describe tool tries to handle —

456
01:02:16,206 --> 01:02:20,006
it listens to what's already in your references
and removes descriptions of things

457
01:02:20,006 --> 01:02:22,226
that already exist.

458
01:02:22,226 --> 01:02:25,846
That's exactly the example of the shoes
and medium shots we talked about.

459
01:02:25,886 --> 01:02:29,266
You can see — we have a shoe reference
and that conflicts with a medium shot.

460
01:02:29,266 --> 01:02:32,265
Let me show another example — I'll remove the shoes.

461
01:02:32,265 --> 01:02:35,196
In short: you converted an image to words
and it didn't override the clothing

462
01:02:35,196 --> 01:02:39,666
because it knew to adapt to the clothing
that was already there.

463
01:02:46,846 --> 01:02:50,346
So — in the Lookbook builder
we didn't take into account

464
01:02:50,346 --> 01:02:54,090
something here — there are stick figures
that help create pose angles.

465
01:02:54,090 --> 01:02:58,662
This is also worth factoring in. You can see
it's inserting a text variable here

466
01:02:58,662 --> 01:03:03,310
that helps lock in the angle.

467
01:03:03,310 --> 01:03:07,330
And that helps create more consistency
in exactly how the figure is positioned.

468
01:03:07,330 --> 01:03:11,006
Depending on what the brand wants —
in principle you can also

469
01:03:11,006 --> 01:03:12,550
select different angles.

470
01:03:12,550 --> 01:03:16,340
If we want to generate front, back, and side view at once,
there's a dedicated button for that — "Add Front Back" —

471
01:03:16,340 --> 01:03:20,730
and you can see it. For any use case —
if we just want

472
01:03:20,730 --> 01:03:22,430
to test by choosing two models,

473
01:03:22,430 --> 01:03:25,210
I can click the plus, pick two models —

474
01:03:25,210 --> 01:03:30,150
and when I click Generate it will create
both options. It'll generate two prompts —

475
01:03:30,150 --> 01:03:33,570
one with this model and one with the other.

476
01:03:33,570 --> 01:03:37,110
I'll leave that — it's a bit advanced,
and I think there's a bug there right now, sorry.

477
01:03:37,110 --> 01:03:41,490
But the idea with the pose is that you can easily
generate front, back, and side views —

478
01:03:41,490 --> 01:03:45,210
which is the basic thing everyone wants.

479
01:03:51,290 --> 01:03:55,270
[In response to a question about face proportions:]
These kinds of bugs usually happen

480
01:03:55,270 --> 01:03:59,770
from a crop that's too close — like just the face.
I'd recommend using the wrench button

481
01:03:59,770 --> 01:04:04,090
and doing "edit with nano" —
write "shoulders and up"

482
01:04:04,090 --> 01:04:07,010
with no clothing visible.
That's very important —

483
01:04:07,010 --> 01:04:10,530
don't let a shirt show,
otherwise it bleeds into the generations.

484
01:04:10,530 --> 01:04:14,270
If you have a black shirt and try to generate
with a dress, it'll produce

485
01:04:14,270 --> 01:04:16,430
a black shirt with a dress layered on top.

486
01:04:16,430 --> 01:04:20,050
Very important — no clothing.
And also — someone asked earlier:

487
01:04:20,050 --> 01:04:24,750
"I only want a face but don't want
to show body type." That's just in the prompt.

488
01:04:24,750 --> 01:04:27,070
Just write the body type in the prompt.

489
01:04:27,070 --> 01:04:30,530
Just write it alongside. That's the next question.

490
01:04:30,530 --> 01:04:34,690
Where do you write the model-specific prompt?

491
01:04:34,730 --> 01:04:37,070
Just in the prompt — it doesn't matter technically,
it's more to help us

492
01:04:37,870 --> 01:04:41,510
keep organized. We want to create a system
where it's easy to avoid mistakes.

493
01:04:41,510 --> 01:04:45,150
There's a lot of room for mistakes.
People always say "it's not coming out right."

494
01:04:45,150 --> 01:04:49,210
Those are always bugs you can fix —
in text, in prompts, or by improving references.

495
01:04:49,210 --> 01:04:53,030
For example, people often say
"the model isn't tall enough."

496
01:04:53,030 --> 01:04:57,830
OK — write "180 centimeters tall."

497
01:04:57,830 --> 01:05:03,546
That's roughly the level of it.

498
01:05:09,906 --> 01:05:13,466
I'll be running forward in the remaining few minutes.

499
01:05:13,466 --> 01:05:19,790
Ultimately, what we want to arrive at is:
once we're happy with the result,

500
01:05:19,810 --> 01:05:22,510
we turn it into a template.

501
01:05:22,610 --> 01:05:26,330
Turn it into a template by clicking this button here —

502
01:05:26,770 --> 01:05:31,410
and choosing — the word "pack" will disappear from the lexicon
and become "template."

503
01:05:31,410 --> 01:05:35,229
Associate it with

504
01:05:36,180 --> 01:05:39,690
a new pack. You can see that a tag is created here —

505
01:05:40,570 --> 01:05:44,310
and from this point we can deliver this digital product
to the client.

506
01:05:44,330 --> 01:05:47,910
The client can run looks against
these templates.

507
01:05:47,910 --> 01:05:54,230
Again — you need several templates
for different types of items.

508
01:05:54,230 --> 01:05:57,360
That's an example of what a lookbook run actually looks like.

509
01:05:57,360 --> 01:06:01,870
In practice, the client will often deliver
a table specifying the styling:

510
01:06:01,870 --> 01:06:04,670
which shirt with which pants,
with which shoes, with which

511
01:06:04,670 --> 01:06:09,680
necklace, with which earrings —
and perhaps in a certain template

512
01:06:09,680 --> 01:06:15,750
she's leaning against the wall more,
and in another template, one leg to the side —

513
01:06:15,750 --> 01:06:19,930
and all of those looks need to run
against the templates we built.

514
01:06:19,930 --> 01:06:23,810
That's the full workflow from A to Z —

515
01:06:23,810 --> 01:06:27,820
from how the brand sees it, to creating the prompts,
to templatizing and running

516
01:06:27,820 --> 01:06:31,820
looks — either in the brand's studio
or by the creative team.

517
01:06:31,820 --> 01:06:35,570
Depending on the brand and what works.
That's broadly it.

518
01:06:35,590 --> 01:06:38,870
[In response to a question about multiple models:]
Yes — we have models
for things more like campaigns —

519
01:06:38,870 --> 01:06:42,538
so there's no issue at all.

520
01:06:43,138 --> 01:06:46,098
[In response to a question about proportions for jewelry/bags:]
As I said earlier — if you and I
can't describe the proportions,

521
01:06:46,098 --> 01:06:48,638
then neither can the model.
That's where it might actually make sense

522
01:06:48,638 --> 01:06:52,678
to photograph it on a model.
Depending on what we want.

523
01:06:52,678 --> 01:06:56,526
Someone asked about jewelry —
yes, there are examples of jewelry,

524
01:06:56,526 --> 01:06:59,906
examples of eyewear too.

525
01:07:00,086 --> 01:07:04,046
[In response to a question about adding size in cm:]
You can try it. I don't think measurements in centimeters
are necessarily how the model thinks —

526
01:07:04,046 --> 01:07:08,318
we have to consider how the model was trained.
Was it trained on images where centimeter size was written?

527
01:07:08,318 --> 01:07:10,318
Probably not on the internet.
But maybe the word "small" or "tiny"

528
01:07:10,318 --> 01:07:14,878
would help — or "big" — depending on what you're working with.
You can also try centimeters. I'm not sure.

529
01:07:14,878 --> 01:07:17,366
[In response to follow-up about model height vs. dress length:]
Honestly it depends on nano banana
and how much it listens.

530
01:07:17,366 --> 01:07:21,466
Sometimes it works better, sometimes less so.
But in general, if we feel the model

531
01:07:21,466 --> 01:07:25,338
should be taller, we'll try adding keywords —
"180cm" and "tall."

532
01:07:25,338 --> 01:07:28,248
It's not a physics simulation —
it's not 3D rendering.

533
01:07:28,248 --> 01:07:32,248
It listens in a relative way — it knows 180 is taller,
so we'll see some change.

534
01:07:46,326 --> 01:07:50,126
[In response to a question about creating new models:]
Sure, absolutely. I didn't touch on this, but

535
01:07:51,038 --> 01:07:54,455
the basic approach is just to write it
in the prompt box —

536
01:07:54,455 --> 01:07:59,558
"unique Israeli woman with French and
Japanese descent, fair skin,

537
01:07:59,558 --> 01:08:03,310
studio white background, shoulders up."

538
01:08:03,310 --> 01:08:07,330
Or use the Describer — those of you
who don't want to write it manually.

539
01:08:07,350 --> 01:08:11,806
Yes, the Describe tool can work for this too.
But really —

540
01:08:11,806 --> 01:08:15,570
go to Pinterest, find models you love,
put them into the Describer —

541
01:08:15,570 --> 01:08:19,558
or what I do in Midjourney is bring in
a few faces I like as reference images,

542
01:08:19,558 --> 01:08:23,066
blend them, make them a "baby" model,
and bring that here.

543
01:08:33,534 --> 01:08:37,506
[In response to a question about print/pattern accuracy:]
In principle that works great — it works very well.

544
01:08:37,506 --> 01:08:41,166
In cases where it doesn't work well —
you can give a detail view

545
01:08:41,166 --> 01:08:43,286
in addition to the reference —

546
01:08:43,286 --> 01:08:44,286
and that will improve it.

547
01:08:45,166 --> 01:08:49,386
We're also working on a custom model of ours
that will improve detail handling.

548
01:08:49,386 --> 01:08:53,226
Coming back to the avatar / model topic —
once you've created a model

549
01:08:53,266 --> 01:08:57,266
that you're happy with — of course,
if you bring one from Midjourney,

550
01:08:57,266 --> 01:09:00,606
just drag and drop into the prompt box and it'll work.

551
01:09:00,606 --> 01:09:04,286
If you created it in Astria,
there's a menu option here:

552
01:09:04,286 --> 01:09:08,346
Convert to Reference — and then she's added to
the prompt box

553
01:09:08,346 --> 01:09:10,386
and given a name automatically.

554
01:09:10,446 --> 01:09:13,826
[In response to a question about using a real photographed model:]
Yes, you can —
just copy-paste her photo. That's it.

555
01:09:13,826 --> 01:09:17,406
But there are legal considerations —
you need to be really careful.

556
01:09:22,426 --> 01:09:26,396
Right — that's between you and whatever
you've agreed with the model — but

557
01:09:27,026 --> 01:09:30,706
[In response to a question about body changes:]
It can't change her body. If I only input her face —

558
01:09:30,706 --> 01:09:37,966
the system has no idea about her body.
The body needs to be specified in the prompt —
you need to write measurements.

559
01:09:37,966 --> 01:09:43,386
This is not face training — it's different.
If consistency of a specific person is very important —

560
01:09:43,386 --> 01:09:47,726
say you're making a clip for a specific singer —
don't do that through the lookbook system.

561
01:09:47,726 --> 01:09:51,006
That whole scenario is less suited to consistent-character work

562
01:09:51,016 --> 01:09:54,886
where the face is very important.
Though there is a solution for that too —

563
01:09:54,886 --> 01:09:57,726
I'll leave it out of this conversation for now,
it's a bit more complex.

564
01:09:57,726 --> 01:10:01,706
[In response to a question about multiple angles:]
Yes — there's a button in the Lookbook:
Add Front, Back, and Side —

565
01:10:01,706 --> 01:10:05,646
and it generates all three prompts at once —
front, back, and side.

566
01:10:05,646 --> 01:10:09,666
But everything we've talked about,
everything on this screen —

567
01:10:09,706 --> 01:10:13,386
is meant for building templates.
Once we lock that in and we're happy,

568
01:10:13,386 --> 01:10:17,596
our goal is to templatize it,
associate it with a template,

569
01:10:17,646 --> 01:10:22,566
and hand it to the brand so they can run it.

570
01:10:22,566 --> 01:10:26,626
So — the prompt helper is just a very naive builder.

571
01:10:26,726 --> 01:10:30,026
When you get to refinements,
you'll need to add — "in back view

572
01:10:30,026 --> 01:10:33,906
I need the hair off to the side" —
and similar details.

573
01:10:33,906 --> 01:10:36,346
So it's a starting point — not the destination.

574
01:10:41,262 --> 01:10:45,802
[In response to a question about the demo examples:]
Those examples you saw at the start?

575
01:10:47,886 --> 01:10:51,666
Yes — that template is what we build
and deliver to the brand.

576
01:10:51,706 --> 01:10:55,646
Then the brand can simply upload a shirt
and get that same lookbook —

577
01:10:55,646 --> 01:10:59,086
more or less the same look and feel.
That's the goal.

578
01:10:59,086 --> 01:11:03,386
The goal is to nail the background,
the expressions, the model, the hair.

579
01:11:03,386 --> 01:11:07,386
Hair band or slick hair pulled back —
all the things the brand cares about —

580
01:11:07,386 --> 01:11:11,930
to create consistency. And of course that varies
by garment type and requires

581
01:11:11,930 --> 01:11:14,146
very specific keywords.

582
01:11:14,146 --> 01:11:17,046
That's the concept broadly.
I also wanted to show something that was sent to me

583
01:11:17,046 --> 01:11:21,076
this morning — it's a Noyz collection
where all the references were uploaded this morning.

584
01:11:21,076 --> 01:11:25,086
Someone asked about multiple people.
You can really start to see the idea emerging —

585
01:11:25,086 --> 01:11:28,066
a kind of main CRM for the brand.

586
01:11:28,066 --> 01:11:31,666
Once all the items and models are in the system,
you can start producing

587
01:11:31,666 --> 01:11:35,206
campaigns and editorials much more easily —
bring in four models with a consistent

588
01:11:35,206 --> 01:11:37,986
background and scene.

589
01:11:37,986 --> 01:11:42,076
This is the entire new collection —
all done in Astria by Shai Yechezkel.

590
01:11:42,076 --> 01:11:45,086
[In response to "are these real models?"]
No — they're virtual.
That's part of the process —

591
01:11:45,086 --> 01:11:48,826
he worked with the brand, built out

592
01:11:51,526 --> 01:11:57,726
the model characters.
For anyone with children, AI is always preferable
because working with child models

593
01:11:57,726 --> 01:12:01,014
involves so many complications.

594
01:12:05,894 --> 01:12:07,614
Look at that — let me show them the video.

595
01:12:07,654 --> 01:12:08,214
Important.

596
01:12:20,534 --> 01:12:24,234
[In response to a question about pack structure:]
I think the standard is to create
about four models for them.

597
01:12:24,234 --> 01:12:28,214
You want to get those approved by the brand —
give them ten options, they choose four,

598
01:12:28,234 --> 01:12:31,914
and those four tell a consistent story
that conveys

599
01:12:35,254 --> 01:12:38,794
the brand identity.

600
01:12:38,794 --> 01:12:42,714
[In response to follow-up on workflow:]
Exactly. Lock in the prompt,
add it to the pack, and from that point

601
01:12:42,714 --> 01:12:43,714
you can run it —

602
01:12:49,834 --> 01:12:53,634
The pack is accessible here in the menu.

603
01:12:53,714 --> 01:12:57,614
Once she's created a generation — you see the image there.
On the right there's a small menu.

604
01:12:57,654 --> 01:13:01,054
Click on the hamburger icon
and you'll see the word "Pack" — which will soon

605
01:13:01,054 --> 01:13:05,326
become "Templates." Click it and there's a New Pack option.
Click New Pack and it creates

606
01:13:05,326 --> 01:13:09,326
a new template you can always return to —
regardless of what garments you put in,

607
01:13:09,326 --> 01:13:13,826
it will apply what you originally defined:
that model, that background, that lighting.

608
01:13:23,482 --> 01:13:27,562
Yes — this is the template we create
and deliver to the brand.

609
01:13:27,582 --> 01:13:31,482
Then the brand can just swap in another garment —
keep the same angle but

610
01:13:31,482 --> 01:13:35,342
change everything else — same background, model, everything.

611
01:13:35,342 --> 01:13:39,502
The goal is to run this for the brand
who has a hundred items from the manufacturer —

612
01:13:39,502 --> 01:13:41,642
run a hundred shirts and a hundred pairs of pants

613
01:13:42,722 --> 01:13:46,642
in the same angles and same appearance
with four different models.

614
01:13:46,642 --> 01:13:50,482
That's the goal — upload another shirt,
or select thirty shirts at once

615
01:13:50,482 --> 01:13:54,252
and click Generate — and run everything
against the template you built.

616
01:14:20,154 --> 01:14:23,894
[In response to a question about using a pack:]
Go up to My Packs.

617
01:14:23,754 --> 01:14:24,763
My Packs.

618
01:14:24,774 --> 01:14:28,654
Here — My Packs. There's the template I built.
I can now choose a different shirt,

619
01:14:28,654 --> 01:14:32,354
upload a different shirt,
and run the template.

620
01:14:37,774 --> 01:14:40,214
[In response to a question about pack contents:]
Yes — the pack can contain

621
01:14:41,294 --> 01:14:45,554
front, side, back views and a certain atmosphere.
The pack contains a collection of prompts —

622
01:14:45,974 --> 01:14:49,194
as you see in the Zara example:
front, back, side, detail view —

623
01:14:49,194 --> 01:14:53,174
and the variations are random. That is,
if you write "model standing against a white background

624
01:14:53,174 --> 01:14:56,814
leaning on an object" —
the object changes randomly.

625
01:14:56,854 --> 01:15:00,094
If you write "chair," there will be a specific chair,
or it will vary.

626
01:15:00,094 --> 01:15:03,434
It depends on how open your prompt is.

627
01:15:10,374 --> 01:15:13,594
[In response to a question about the video:]
Yes, yes — the video was also done in Astria.

628
01:15:13,654 --> 01:15:18,834
[In response to a question about generating video:]
There's a video button — a simple one —
that gives you all available models,

629
01:15:18,874 --> 01:15:22,394
and there's a switcher that lets you
switch to video mode, choose a model,

630
01:15:22,394 --> 01:15:26,482
choose duration, write a prompt —
and of course the important thing is

631
01:15:26,482 --> 01:15:30,002
that you can templatize this too.
You can create a scenario

632
01:15:30,002 --> 01:15:34,362
where the model walks into a scene, turns around,
exits — just like in a real product page video.

633
01:15:34,362 --> 01:15:36,212
And that goes into the template too.

634
01:15:39,962 --> 01:15:43,882
[In response to a question about production time for video:]
I think part of what makes it fast
comes from the system itself.

635
01:15:43,882 --> 01:15:47,762
A big part of the work was done beforehand —
all the items were already in the system,

636
01:15:47,762 --> 01:15:51,542
all the models too.
The Total Look was already ready in the system,

637
01:15:51,542 --> 01:15:54,602
and all that remained was composing them into a scene.
The scene itself was built before the video.

638
01:15:54,602 --> 01:15:58,962
You can see it on the website already.
That concept — the hot air balloon,

639
01:15:58,962 --> 01:16:02,402
that scene — all happened before the video,
even before the client asked for video.

640
01:16:02,402 --> 01:16:06,462
Then it was very easy to say:
now we're ready for video.

641
01:16:06,462 --> 01:16:10,262
That's the whole build-up we do here.
We go from the most basic —

642
01:16:10,262 --> 01:16:13,882
the studio lookbook, very clean with the models —
up to campaign

643
01:16:13,882 --> 01:16:17,022
and editorial, all the way to video.
The system is meant

644
01:16:17,022 --> 01:16:20,862
to cover everything —
and all of it needs

645
